  "prompt": "Is O-ve universal donor?",
  "response": "Yes, O-negative (O-) blood type is often referred to as the universal donor type for red blood cells. This is because O- blood does not have A or B antigens on the surface of the red blood cells, nor does it have the Rh factor, making it compatible with all other blood types in emergency transfusions. However, it\u2019s important to note that while O- can be given to any patient in need of red blood cells, other blood component transfusions (like plasma) have different compatibility rules.",
